<h2>Declarative Component Adapter</h2>
<p>
    The Declarative Component Adapter is the intended implementation of the
    <a href="/blocks/component/">Component block</a> — the <code>&lt;component&gt;</code> element. It is a
    <strong>deterministic, build-time, AST-based transform</strong> that lowers each declarative
    definition into an equivalent class-based custom element plus
    <code>customElements.define()</code>. It is not a browser-side interpreter; nothing in the tier-1
    output depends on a runtime beyond baseline DOM APIs.
</p>

<section class="section-card fui-card">
    <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
        <strong>Concept Phase.</strong> Sibling to the
        <a href="/adapters/functional-component-adapter/">Functional Component Adapter</a> (functional → class) and
        in the lineage of the canonical <a href="/adapters/html-adapter/">HTML Adapter</a>'s
        AST-transformation work. Whether it stays standalone or folds into the HTML Adapter is an
        open point (<strong>DC-6</strong>, see the
        <a href="/blocks/component/#open-questions">Component block</a>).
    </p>
</section>

<section class="section-card fui-card">
    <h3 id="concept">Concept</h3>
    <p>The transform takes declarative markup in — the component's own children are the template (no nested <code>&lt;template&gt;</code> needed):</p>
    {% highlight "html" %}
<component name="user-card" shadow="open">
  <style>:host { display: block }</style>
  <h3><slot name="title">Untitled</slot></h3>
  <slot></slot>
</component>
    {% endhighlight %}
    <p>…and deterministically emits the class form out:</p>
    {% highlight "typescript" %}
const TEMPLATE = document.createElement('template');
TEMPLATE.innerHTML =
  `<style>:host { display: block }</style>` +
  `<h3><slot name="title">Untitled</slot></h3><slot></slot>`;

class UserCard extends HTMLElement {
  #root = this.shadowRoot;
  connectedCallback() {
    this.#root ??= this.attachShadow({ mode: 'open' });
    if (!this.#root.childNodes.length) this.#root.append(TEMPLATE.content.cloneNode(true));
  }
}
customElements.define('user-card', UserCard);
    {% endhighlight %}
    <p>
        The class name is derived from <code>name</code> (kebab → PascalCase); <code>shadow</code>
        selects the <code>attachShadow</code> mode (or light DOM for <code>none</code>); the
        component's children become the cloned render source. This is the same lowering
        Svelte's compiler and Lit-style tooling already perform.
    </p>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
        Both authoring forms lower identically: the <strong>implicit</strong> form (children are the
        template) and the <strong>explicit</strong> form (a lone direct-child <code>&lt;template&gt;</code>,
        kept inert before the transform runs). Because the transform reads source text at build time,
        the implicit form is safe — the children never go live in a browser (DC-11).
    </p>
</section>

<section class="section-card fui-card">
    <h3 id="guarantees">Determinism guarantees</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Byte-identical output</strong> for identical input — stable member ordering, no timestamps or content hashes — so generated files diff cleanly and cache well.</li>
        <li><strong>AST-based, not string-rewriting</strong> — the definition is parsed to an AST and emitted from the AST; source is never regex-patched.</li>
        <li><strong>Zero residual runtime (tier 1)</strong> — output uses only baseline <code>attachShadow</code>, <code>&lt;template&gt;.content.cloneNode</code>, and <code>customElements.define()</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Idempotent registration</strong> — the emitted <code>connectedCallback</code> no-ops if the tree is already populated (SSR / Declarative Shadow DOM hydration safe).</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
        The deterministic, AST-based emitter could be built on the workspace's existing
        esbuild / TypeScript tooling. Concrete code lives in the reference implementation
        (Frontier UI), not in this canonical repo.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="section-card fui-card">
    <h3 id="directionality">Directionality &amp; compatibility</h3>
    <p>
        Unlike the <a href="/adapters/jsx-adapter/">JSX adapter</a> — a <strong>two-way</strong>, reversible
        <em>mirror</em> of HTML (the same element tree in two spellings, lossless round-trip) — the Declarative
        Component adapter is <strong>one-way</strong>: it <em>lowers</em> a declarative definition to a class. A
        class is strictly more expressive than a declarative definition (arbitrary lifecycle, imperative logic,
        observed attributes), so <code>class → &lt;component&gt;</code> is not generally recoverable.
    </p>
    <we-data-table><table>
        <tr><th></th><th>JSX adapter</th><th>Declarative Component adapter</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Maps</td><td>HTML ⇄ JSX — same tree, two spellings</td><td>declarative <code>&lt;component&gt;</code> → class custom element</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Directionality</td><td><strong>Two-way</strong> (bidirectional)</td><td><strong>One-way</strong> (lowering / desugaring)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Round-trip</td><td>Lossless for named constructs; inline closures &amp; eager interpolation lossy</td><td>Only the exact generated class shape reverses; arbitrary classes do not</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Transform time</td><td>Build-time AST (<code>jsxToHtml</code>/<code>htmlToJsx</code>)</td><td>Build-time AST (runtime twin in the playground)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Output</td><td>The other authoring format (peer)</td><td>A registered custom element (lower layer)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Category</td><td>Rendering (format peer of HTML)</td><td>Syntax (sugar → class)</td></tr>
    </table></we-data-table>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
        So the <a href="/blocks/component/">block page's</a> declarative↔class toggle shows <em>input beside
        generated output</em>, not two interchangeable spellings. The two adapters <strong>compose</strong>: a
        <code>&lt;component&gt;</code> definition can itself be authored in JSX spelling, which the JSX adapter
        reverses to HTML, which this adapter then lowers to a class.
    </p>
</section>

